<h2>Your Google Business Profile: The Foundation of Local SEO</h2>
<p>Your <strong><a href="/articles/google-business-profile-kenya">Google Business Profile (GBP)</a></strong> is the free listing that appears in Google Maps and in the local "pack" of results at the top of a search page. If you haven't claimed and optimised yours, you're invisible in local search.</p>
<p>A fully optimised GBP includes:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Business name</strong>, exactly as it appears on your signage and website</li>
  <li><strong>Category</strong>, be specific (not just "business," but "dental clinic" or "civil engineering company")</li>
  <li><strong>Address</strong>, your physical location, verified by Google</li>
  <li><strong>Phone number</strong>, a Kenyan mobile or landline you answer</li>
  <li><strong>Website URL</strong>, linking to your website</li>
  <li><strong>Business hours</strong>, including holiday hours</li>
  <li><strong>Photos</strong>, high-quality images of your premises, team, and products/services</li>
  <li><strong>Services / products list</strong>, detailed, keyword-rich descriptions</li>
  <li><strong>Regular posts</strong>, weekly updates, offers, or news</li>
</ul>

<h2>Google Reviews: The Most Powerful Local SEO Signal</h2>
<p>Businesses with more positive reviews rank higher in local search. Reviews also directly influence whether a customer contacts you — 87% of consumers read online reviews before choosing a local business.</p>
<p>A systematic approach to getting reviews:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Ask satisfied customers directly, "Would you mind leaving us a quick Google review? It helps a lot."</li>
  <li>Send a follow-up WhatsApp message with your Google review link</li>
  <li>Add a review request to your email signatures</li>
  <li>Respond to every review, positive and negative, within 48 hours</li>
</ul>
<p>Aim to get at least 10 reviews in your first month. 50+ reviews puts you in a strong position relative to most Kenyan competitors.</p>

<h2>Local Keyword Targeting on Your Website</h2>
<p>Your website needs to tell Google clearly where you operate and what you do. This means using location-specific keywords naturally throughout your content.</p>
<p>Examples:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Instead of "we offer plumbing services," write "we offer plumbing services in Westlands and Parklands, Nairobi"</li>
  <li>Instead of "contact our law firm," write "contact our law firm in Upperhill, Nairobi"</li>
  <li>Create a dedicated page for each area you serve (e.g., "Web Design Services in Mombasa")</li>
</ul>

<h2>NAP Consistency: Name, Address, Phone</h2>
<p>Your business Name, Address, and Phone number should be <em>identical</em> across every place it appears online, your website, Google Business Profile, Facebook page, LinkedIn, directories like Yellow Pages Kenya, and any other mentions. Inconsistencies confuse Google and dilute your local authority.</p>

<h2>Local Link Building</h2>
<p>Links from other local websites signal to Google that your business is legitimate and established in the area. How to get local links:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Join local business associations (Kenya National Chamber of Commerce and Industry)</li>
  <li>Partner with complementary local businesses and exchange links</li>
  <li>Get listed in Kenyan business directories (Biashara Kenya, Yellow Pages Kenya)</li>
  <li>Sponsor local events and get a link from their website</li>
  <li>Write guest articles for local industry publications</li>
</ul>

